[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6{ With this move, we enter the Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD). The idea of this LTR is to provide you with a very solid repertoire, but without running away from complications when needed and always trying to give you interesting alternatives to fight for the win.    I have spent several months working to complete this project, trying to give you the best possible lines.  Naturally, the whole course has been tested with super engines. Nowadays, having a repertoire without the use of Stockfish is complete nonsense, but let’s not forget that Stockfish only gives you the best move, but it will not tell you why that is the best move. That is why I am here, to explain to you every possible line, talking about plans, ideas, and reasons behind every move.    There are also some positions with an evaluation of equality according to the engines but extremely difficult to play in practice, or the other way around. We should not be happy with an equal position where it is very tough to play for a human. That is why I am also here, to identify those situations and give you the best possible lines for your games.    Another important remark is that I would never recommend anything that I am not willing to play myself. I have played the Queen’s Gambit Declined in many of my games and will continue to do so since it is a very nice opening! The Queen’s Gambit Declined has been one of the most popular responses to the Queen’s Gambit for years. In the 1927 World Chess Championship, the Queen’s Gambit Declined was played in 32 out of 34 games!    I reached 2450 FIDE rating points when I was around 18 years old, and until that point, my only openings with the black pieces against  1.d4  were the King’s Indian and the Benko Gambit. I still enjoy playing them a lot, but at that point, I realized that against strong grandmasters, I really needed to have something more solid in my pocket, and that is how I started to play the Nimzo-Indian and the QGD.    I have tried the QGD as well against the world's number 1, Magnus Carlsen. I would love to say that I crashed him in style, sacrificing a bishop on  h2  and checkmating him in the middle of the board, but as you can imagine, that is very far from reality. Even though I got nice positions, he actually beat me 8.5 vs. 0.5 in an online match, and I celebrated that half-point as if Spain won the football World Cup, and I say “celebrated” because this match was played in the 'Banter Blitz Cup” of chess24, a very nice tournament that I created with my colleague Divis, where players need to play and talk at the same time. That time, the final was Carlsen vs. Firouzja and was watched by thousands of people!    Probably my best win using the QGD was against Paco Vallejo (2700 player and number 1 of Spain) in the Spanish Championship of 2019.    From this point, White has several ways to proceed, and in this introductory mini-chapter, I will tell you what is covered and where! }
3. Nf3( 3.Nc3 { is covered in  chapter 14 , where we propose the interesting }3...Be7! { , leading to very complex and fun positions to play. } )( 3.cxd5 { leads to the Accelerated Exchange Variation, which is covered in  chapter 15 . } )
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( 4.Bg5 { is covered in  chapter 11 , }4.Bf4 { is studied in  chapter 12 , }4.e3 { is a solid move and covered in  chapter 13 , while }4.g3 { is naturally the Catalan, and is deeply studied in chapters  1 ,  2 ,  3 , and  4 . } )
4. Be7
5. Bg5( 5.Bf4 { , these modern lines are covered in  chapter 6 , and the QGD-Catalan Hybrid with }5.g3 { is analyzed in  chapter 10 . } )
5. h6
6. Bh4( 6.Bxf6 { can be studied in  chapter 7 . } )
6. O-O
7. e3
7. Ne4{ One of my favorite lines is the Lasker Variation (chapters  8  and  9 ), which is an example of how things can continue in the Queen's Gambit Declined. With the last move, Black, in principle, forces the exchange of two minor pieces and thus relieves the defense. The maneuver can be traced back to the first and only German World Champion, Emanuel Lasker.    I perfectly remember the first game that I played with the Lasker Variation. Some years ago, it was a rainy day at the super-strong Gibraltar Open. Gibraltar is a very nice place, which is in fact very close to my hometown (Granada, in the south of Spain). Usually, most players stay in La Línea, a small village on the Spanish side, because Gibraltar can be extremely expensive sometimes.    I was one of these guys and left my hotel intending to go to “La Caleta Hotel” in Gibraltar, to the playing hall. I arrived at the border, and the police officer asked for my ID. I do not know what happened, but my ID had a big hole in the middle. Therefore, the officer did not want to let me in. After 30 minutes of discussion, he took pity on me, and I managed to arrive at the playing hall right before losing on time. My opponent was my good friend and number 1 of Italy, GM Daniele Vocaturo. We entered the Lasker Variation, and he opted for the super-aggressive  variation with 10.g4 . The game ended in a draw after 6 hours of fight and 94 moves.    I hope that you guys enjoy this work! }
