[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4{ Welcome to the first chapter on the Catalan! This is one of the most important ones in the whole course. Many strong players employ this opening and theory is constantly evolving.    It is one of the most solid openings and White hopes for small edges and tries to build up pressure slowly. There are many possible recipes against the Catalan, but I do hope that you will enjoy my recommendation! }
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ This move does not define yet if White wants to play with  Nc3 ,  Bg5 , or  g3 ... }
3. Nf6
4. g3{ And the Catalan is here. This is the main move order and the main line. }
4. dxc4{ Of course, there are a lot of possible moves for Black, but this line with ... c5  and ... Nc6  is a very interesting and solid idea that GM Wesley So employed in a lot of games and with very good results. }
5. Bg2{ The main line. }
5. c5{ Here we go with ... c5  and ... Nc6 , hitting in the center quickly. }
6. O-O
6. Nc6
7. Qa4{ One of the main lines. White is intending to play  Ne5  next move. }
7. Bd7{ Unpinning the knight. }
8. dxc5
8. Bxc5
9. Qxc4
9. Be7
10. Nc3
10. O-O
11. e4{ This makes sense, occupying the center and restricting the  f6 -knight. }
11. Qa5{ Making room for the rooks on  d8  and  c8 . }
12. Rd1
12. Rad8( 12...Rfd8 { is another interesting move for Black, with the idea }{ of ... Be8 . Rock solid. }13.Qe2 Be8 14.Bd2 Qb6 15.Be3 Qa5 { and a repetition will arise after }16.Bd2 Qb6 17.Be3 Qa5 { as in ½-½ Cheng-Melkumyan, Canberra 2022. } )
13. Qe2
13. Bc8{ Controlling the d-file. }
14. Bd2
14. Qh5{ With ... e5  and ... Bg4  or ... Bh3  in mind. We can even think about starting an attack. :) }
15. e5{ A very risky move. A friend of mine used to say that 'after playing  e5  in these kinds of positions, either you checkmate your opponent or you lose the endgame.' This pawn can be very weak in certain positions or endgames! }
15. Nd7
16. Bf4
16. g5{ This move equalizes the position. }
17. Nxg5
17. Qxe2
18. Nxe2
18. Ndxe5{ ½-½ Eljanov-Wojtaszek, Batumi 2018. }
