1. d4{ Welcome to the first chapter on the Catalan! This is one of the most important ones in the whole course. Many strong players employ this opening and theory is constantly evolving.    It is one of the most solid openings and White hopes for small edges and tries to build up pressure slowly. There are many possible recipes against the Catalan, but I do hope that you will enjoy my recommendation! }
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ This move does not define yet if White wants to play with  Nc3 ,  Bg5 , or  g3 ... }
3. Nf6
4. g3{ And the Catalan is here. This is the main move order and the main line. }
4. dxc4{ Of course, there are a lot of possible moves for Black, but this line with ... c5  and ... Nc6  is a very interesting and solid idea that GM Wesley So employed in a lot of games and with very good results. }
5. Bg2{ The main line. }
5. c5{ Here we go with ... c5  and ... Nc6 , hitting in the center quickly. }
6. O-O
6. Nc6
7. dxc5( 7.dxc5 { and }7.Qa4 { are the main lines for White, but in the last years, }7.dxc5 { is more popular. } )
7. Qxd1{ White wants to take on  c4  quickly. }
8. Rxd1
8. Bxc5
9. Nbd2( { The main move, but }9.Nfd2 { deserves consideration. } )
9. c3{ Forcing White to take on  c3 , breaking the structure. The good news is that our pawn structure will be slightly better. The bad news is that White can use the b-file along with the monster on  g2  to put pressure on the queenside and  b7  and  c6 . }
10. bxc3
10. O-O
11. Nb3( 11.Bb2 { transposes to the main lines. } )
11. Be7
12. Nfd4{ This is the line that GM Narayanan recommends in his Chessable course. GM Wesley So equalizes without problems here. }( 12.Bb2 { transposes to the  main line  with }12.c4 { , while }12.Bg5 e5! { leads to a good position for Black. } )
12. Nxd4
13. cxd4{ White manages to fix the pawn structure. }
13. Nd5{ The best move, closing in the  g2 -bishop and preparing ... Nc3  as well as ... b6  and ... Bb7 . Also, Black can play ... f5 , fighting against the  e4  push. There are many options for White now. }
14. e4{ A normal move, but it is not dangerous for Black. }
14. Nc3{ The best move, of course! }
15. Rd3
15. Ne2+{ Let's get the bishop pair! }
16. Kh1
16. b6( { In Wojtaszek's footsteps, planning ... Ba6  next, but }16...Nxc1 { is perfectly playable as well. } )
17. Bb2
17. Ba6
18. Re3
18. Rac8{ Played with the ... Rc2  idea in mind. }
19. Rb1
19. Rc2( { This is a forced repetition for both sides: }20.Na1 Rd2 21.Nb3 Rc2 22.Na1 Rd2 23.Nb3 Rc2 { ½-½ Svidler-Wojtaszek, Sochi 2015. } )
