[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined − Introduction"]
[Black "QGD − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6( { Here we go with the Queen's Gambit Declined. The QGD has the reputation of being one of Black's most reliable defenses against   }1.d4 { . In this situation, White will try to exploit the passivity of Black's light-squared bishop, and Black will try to release it, trade it, or prove that while passive, the bishop has a useful defensive role.    There are other possibilities for Black on the second move:   }2...c6 { − Slav Defense, }2...e5 { − Albin Countergambit, }2...Nc6 { – Chigorin Defense, }2...Bf5 { – Baltic Defense, }2...c5 { − Symmetrical Defense (or Austrian Defense).    }{ In the main variation, Black develops the bishop to  e7  and prepares to castle kingside. That is a very important position in chess theory. White now develops the dark-squared bishop to  g5  or  f4  and afterwards takes care of the development of the kingside. Black does the opposite. After the kingside has been developed, Black gradually brings the pieces on the queenside into play. The light-squared bishop on  c8  is often fianchettoed to  b7  or developed along the  c8 - h3  diagonal if White exchanges pawns on  d5 .    The Queen’s Gambit Declined has been one of the most popular responses to the Queen’s Gambit for years. In the 1927 World Chess Championship, the QGD was played in 32 out of 34 games!    The Lasker Variation is an example of how things can continue in the Queen's Gambit Declined. }{ With   }7...Ne4 { , Black forces in principle the exchange of two minor pieces and thus relieves the defense. The maneuver can be traced back to the first and only German World Champion, Emanuel Lasker. } )
