[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Be7
5. Bf4( { The new modern lines. }5.Bf4 { is more popular today than }5.Bg5 { and there are a lot of tricky move orders. So we should know what we are doing here! } )
5. O-O
6. e3( 6.c5 { is defining White's structure too early, offering Black the possibility to take over immediately with }6...b6 { since }7.b4 a5 8.a3 Ne4 { is clearly in our favor, while  }7.cxb6 axb6 { only helps }{ Black open the file for the a-rook, and strengthens the ... c5  push as well. } )
6. b6( { The first important moment. Black can play }6...c5 { or }6...Nbd7 { , which are perfectly fine moves. }6...b6 { is a more quiet move. Here, }{ White has many options, including taking on  d5 , developing the bishop, or other moves like }{   }7.Qc2 { , }7.Rc1 { , }7.a3 { , etc. } )
7. Qc2{ A very aggressive line, with long castle ideas. We need to be careful! }
7. c5( { I think this is the most secure move for Black. }7...Ba6 { is another interesting option, but the Dubov-Svane game is an example of what can go wrong for us. } )
8. dxc5( 8.cxd5 Nxd5 { is the move to equalize. } )
8. bxc5( { This is the idea, }8...Bxc5 { is not accurate, as }9.Rd1 { is coming }{ and the pressure on  d5  is unpleasant. } )
9. Rd1( 9.Rd1 { is the main line and the main idea. }9.O-O-O { is very optimistic, as after }9...Nc6 { , White's king is in trouble. } )( 9.cxd5 Nxd5 { again is the best move for Black, }{ with ... Nc6  on the next move and a very comfortable position. } )( 9.Be2 Nc6 10.O-O Qb6 { and Black's plan }{ is ... Ba6  and putting the rooks on  d8  and  c8 . } )
9. Nc6
10. cxd5( { After }10.Be2 Qb6 { , White can't take two times }{ on  d5  since ... Nb4  is a winning fork for Black. }11.O-O { and now }...Rd8 { , }...Ba6 { , and Black's position is perfect. } )
10. Nxd5( { This move is a novelty that the computer likes, which is better than }10...exd5 { since Black will struggle to }{ protect  d5 . The point is that after an eventual ... Be6 , White can try to annoy us with  Ng5 . If the knights are off the board, Black controls the  g5 -square with the  e7 -bishop. } )
11. Bc4
11. Qa5
12. Bxd5( 12.O-O Nxf4 13.exf4 Rb8 { with active play for Black. } )
12. Nb4
13. Qd2
13. Nxd5{ Multiple exchanges! }
14. Nxd5
14. Qxd2+
15. Rxd2
15. exd5
16. Rxd5
16. Be6{ Black is capturing the  a2 -pawn on the next move and therefore enjoying the bishop pair and a nice 2 vs. 1 on the queenside. }
