10. cxd5( { After }10.Be2 Qb6 { , White can't take two times }{ on  d5  since ... Nb4  is a winning fork for Black. }11.O-O { and now }...Rd8 { , }...Ba6 { , and Black's position is perfect. } )
10. Nxd5( { This move is a novelty that the computer likes, which is better than }10...exd5 { since Black will struggle to }{ protect  d5 . The point is that after an eventual ... Be6 , White can try to annoy us with  Ng5 . If the knights are off the board, Black controls the  g5 -square with the  e7 -bishop. } )
11. Qa4( 11.Nxd5 exd5 { and ... Be6  next, with a pleasant game. } )
11. Ncb4( 11...Nd4 { is a very tricky move, perfectly possible, and }11...Bb7 { is the other normal move. } )
12. Nxd5( 12.Be2 Bd7 { and ... Nxf4  next. } )( { If }12.Bb5 a6 13.O-O Bb7 { and Black is fine, }{ with ... Qb6  to follow. } )
12. Nxd5( 12...exd5? { fails to }13.a3 Bd7 14.Bb5 Bxb5 15.Qxb5 Nc2 16.Kd2 { and Black has a problem with the knight. } )
13. Bb5( { Not }13.e4 Bd7! 14.Bb5 Qb6!  )
13. Qb6{ Black can take on  f4  and play ... Bf6  and ... Bb7  in the next moves. }
