5. Bf4( { The new modern lines. }5.Bf4 { is more popular today than }5.Bg5 { and there are a lot of tricky move orders. So we should know what we are doing here! } )
5. O-O
6. e3( 6.c5 { is defining White's structure too early, offering Black the possibility to take over immediately with }6...b6 { since }7.b4 a5 8.a3 Ne4 { is clearly in our favor, while  }7.cxb6 axb6 { only helps }{ Black open the file for the a-rook, and strengthens the ... c5  push as well. } )
6. b6( { The first important moment. Black can play }6...c5 { or }6...Nbd7 { , which are perfectly fine moves. }6...b6 { is a more quiet move. Here, }{ White has many options, including taking on  d5 , developing the bishop, or other moves like }{   }7.Qc2 { , }7.Rc1 { , }7.a3 { , etc. } )
7. cxd5
7. Nxd5( 7...exd5 { leads to White's dream in the Carlsbad structure. } )
8. Nxd5
8. Qxd5( { I think this move is better than }8...exd5 { , which is also possible, of course. } )
9. Bxc7{ Taking the  c7 -pawn is possible, but Black's activity is tremendous. }
9. Bb4+
10. Nd2
10. Nc6{ With fast development. }
11. a3( 11.f3 { is the computer option, but Black can play }11...Bd7 { and ... Rac8 , and in some variations, ... Nxd4  could be dangerous. This position is unpleasant for a human with the white pieces! } )
11. Bxd2+
12. Qxd2
12. Na5{ ... Nb3  is coming, be careful! }
13. Qd3( 13.Qc3 { is a dubious move, }13...Bb7 14.b4 Nb3 15.Rb1 Rfc8! { and the control of the c-file compensates the pawn. } )( 13.Qb4 { is similar to  Qc3 . Black can play }13...Bb7 { and ... Rfc8  next; activity activity activity! } )( { After }13.Rd1 { , Black must play }13...Bd7 14.b4 Rfc8 { , with similar ideas. } )
13. Nb3
14. Rd1
14. Bd7{ ... Rfc8  is coming again! }
15. Bd6
15. Rfc8
16. e4
16. Qxd6
17. Qxb3
17. Qf4
18. Qe3{ The rook goes to  c2 , and activity is more important than the pawn. }
