3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Be7
5. Bg5{ Here we go with the main line. }
5. h6{ Our main move. White must decide to take on  f6  or play  Bh4 , and we will deeply analyze these two moves! }
6. Bh4
6. O-O
7. e3
7. Ne4{ This move defines the Lasker Variation. It is one of the most solid approaches against the Queen's Gambit. I have employed this line in many of my games.    Until I reached 2460-2470 FIDE rating, I only played the King's Indian. I realized that I needed another option more solid against the strong GMs, and at that point, I studied the Queen's Gambit Declined and in particular the Lasker Variation. }( { If you study these lines correctly, it will be very hard for your opponent to get an advantage out of the opening. The main line is }8.Bxe7 { , but }8.Bg3 { is possible too. } )
8. Bg3{ I faced this move in an online tournament (the Iberoamerican Championship) against my good friend, the Cuban GM Omar Almeida. It has a lot of venom. If Black captures on  g3 , White can attack along the h-file in many variations. }
8. c5{ It is important to hit the center quickly. }
9. cxd5( 9.Bd3 Nxg3 10.hxg3 dxc4 11.Bxc4 cxd4 12.exd4 Nc6 { leads to a very good position for Black. } )
9. exd5
10. Bd3( 10.dxc5 Nxc3 11.bxc3 Nd7 12.Bd6 Nf6 { seems good for Black. } )
10. Nxg3
11. hxg3
11. cxd4( 11...c4 12.Bc2 Nc6 { is another interesting alternative for Black. } )
12. Nxd4
12. Nc6
13. Bc2
13. Bf6{ Black is slightly better. Ideas: ... Nxd4 , ... Be6 , ... Qb6 . }
