16. Nf6{ The position is balanced. White has to watch out now, as ... Ng4  is a threat. Moreover, we can develop naturally with ... Bd7 , ... Rfe8 , and possibly ... Qg5  or ... a5 , depending on the circumstances. }( { For example, a cute sample line is }17.h3 { , }{ preventing ... Ng4 , }17...Bd7 18.Rce1 Rfe8 19.e4 Bxh3 { ( }19...Qg5 { is also good, to keep the game going)   }20.gxh3 Qg5+ 21.Kh2 ( 21.Kh1 Qh4 22.Kh2 Qf4+ { ( }22...Ng4+? { fails to }23.Kg2 Qg5 24.Qc1! Ne3+ 25.Kf3 Nxf1 26.Qxg5 { and White has a better endgame with the two minor pieces for the rook.)   }23.Kg2 Qg5+ { , when a draw is in sight. If White tries to escape the threefold repetition by playing }24.Kh1 Qh4 25.f3 { , now Black can rely on }25...Nh5 26.Qf2 Qxh3+ 27.Qh2 Ng3+ 28.Kg1 Qxh2+ 29.Kxh2 Nxf1+ { , with a better version of the endgame. } )21...Ng4+ { ( }21...Qf4+ { is equally good)   }22.Kh1 Qh5 { ( }22...Qh4? { runs into the same problem we've seen before: }23.Kg2 Qg5 24.Qc1± { )   }23.Kg2 Qg6 24.Kh1 Qh5= { and a draw can't be avoided. } )
