7. Ne4{ This move defines the Lasker Variation. It is one of the most solid approaches against the Queen's Gambit. I have employed this line in many of my games.    Until I reached 2460-2470 FIDE rating, I only played the King's Indian. I realized that I needed another option more solid against the strong GMs, and at that point, I studied the Queen's Gambit Declined and in particular the Lasker Variation. }( { If you study these lines correctly, it will be very hard for your opponent to get an advantage out of the opening. The main line is }8.Bxe7 { , but }8.Bg3 { is possible too. } )
8. Bxe7
8. Qxe7{ White has many options to continue. }
9. Rc1( { The main line at this moment. A rare idea is }9.Nxe4 dxe4 10.Nd2 { and here, }10...f5 { , }{ defending  e4 , is a good move. }10...e5 { with some tricky ideas is good too, but I prefer }10...f5 { followed by ... e5  on the next move. } )
9. c6{ Defending  d5 , and now there are many options for White again. }
10. Be2{ Another interesting option for White, of course! }
10. Nxc3
11. Rxc3
11. dxc4
12. Bxc4{ After some exchanges, Black can develop with ... Nd7  and ... e5  or ... c5  quickly, with some ... b6  if necessary. }
12. Nd7
13. O-O( { There are many options for Black now: }13...b6 { , }13...e5 { , }13...c5 { , and }13...a5 { are possible. } )
13. c5{ It is not the most played move, but I think Black has a good and healthy position. }
14. Bb5( { The main move, as }14.dxc5 Nxc5 15.Qc2 Bd7 { is not dangerous for Black. } )( 14.Qc2 cxd4 15.Nxd4 Nf6 { followed by ... Bd7  is perfectly fine for Black. } )
14. cxd4
15. Qxd4( 15.Nxd4 Nf6 { followed by ... Rd8  or ... Bd7  seems good for Black. } )
15. Nf6
16. Qe5{ An important alternative for White. }
16. Rd8
17. Rfc1( { After }17.Rc7 { , Black can play }17...Qf8 { with the idea of }{ playing ... Nd5 , kicking the rook from the seventh rank, and following up with ... Bd7 , completing development. } )
17. Bd7
18. Rc7
18. a6{ With normal development for Black. }
19. Be2
19. Qb4{ The position is equal. }
