1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Be7
5. g3{ With this move, White transposes to a rare order of the Catalan with the knight on  c3 . }
5. O-O( 5...O-O { is preferable since }5...dxc4 { allows }6.Qa4+ { , getting the pawn back immediately. } )
6. Bg2
6. dxc4( { I think this is the best move for Black. Another idea is to play }6...c6 { and ... Nbd7 , but White can play with castle and  Nd2 , preparing for a quick  e4 . } )
7. O-O( { After }7.Qa4 a6 8.Qxc4 b5 { followed by ... Bb7  and ... c5 , Black has no problems and has solved the issue of the light-squared bishop. } )
7. Nc6{ An important move, attacking on  d4 . Now  Ne5  is not possible for White. }
8. e4{ This is not dangerous for Black in my opinion, but we need to be careful. There are many ideas for White! }
8. a6( { The best move. }8...Rb8 { is another good try for Black in this position, but I prefer the first one. Naturally, the idea is to protect }{ the  c4 -pawn for good. } )
9. Qe2
9. b5( { The best choice for Black. }9...Nxd4 { is also possible, but }{ defending the  c4 -pawn is the best move. } )
10. Rd1
10. Nb4
11. Ne1{ Controlling ... Nd3 . }
11. Bb7( 11...c5 { was played in 0-1 Sinanan-Adams, Los Angeles 2011, but after }12.dxc5! { , the position is completely balanced. } )
12. Bf4
12. Re8{ Black is perfectly okay, but White has some compensation for the pawn. Ideas: ... Bf8  and ... Qc8  followed by ... c6  or ... c5 . }
