3. Be7( { This move is recommended by GM Colovic in his QGD Chessable course and is one that we will recommend as well. The move }3...Nf6 { is naturally the other main alternative. }3...Be7 { is a smart attempt to avoid the most critical lines of the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit: }3...Nf6 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bg5 Be7 6.e3 c6 7.Bd3 { followed by  Nge2 . } )
4. cxd5( { The Exchange Variation − }4.cxd5 { is the main move. }4.Nf3 Nf6 { transposes to  other chapters  of this course. } )
4. exd5
5. Bf4
5. c6{ ... Bf5  is the idea on the next move, as always! Easy to remember. }
6. e3
6. Bf5{ The natural move. }
7. g4{ One of the most aggressive and fun lines to play! I have played this line with  3...Be7  twice in classical chess, and in both games I entered this variation. Get ready for some exciting chess! }
7. Be6( 7...Bg6 { is the other alternative, but the computers don't like the resulting positions. } )
8. h3{ The most secure move, defending the pawn on  g4 . }
8. Nd7{ Black develops the queen's knight first. }
9. Bd3
9. g5( { The move }9...h5 { , recommended in the QGD Chessable course of GM Colovic, is also possible, but this will be our choice. Once again, now you have two decent options! } )
10. Bh2
10. h5{ The typical reaction. }
11. f3
11. Nb6{ With the idea of playing ... Bd6 , trading the dangerous dark-squared bishop. }
12. Qc2
12. Bd6{ I think this is a crucial move. The white bishop on  h2  is too strong, and it makes sense to trade it. }
13. O-O-O
13. Bxh2
14. Rxh2( 14.Qxh2 Qe7 { and long castle. } )
14. Qc7{ Threatening to take on  g4  twice and also preparing to castle queenside. }
15. Rg2
15. hxg4
16. hxg4
16. O-O-O{ ½-½ Mchedlishvili-Magalashvili, Tbilisi 2018. Ideas: ... Nf6 , ... Rh4 , ... Nc4 . }
