1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3{ Welcome to the London System chapter. It is gaining a lot of popularity in the last few years among club players but also among top grandmasters. Magnus Carlsen has used it as a main weapon in a couple of Rapid World Championships.    In the last World Championship in 2023, Ding Liren won a nice game against Nepo with the white pieces. The London System deserves very serious attention. Let's go! }
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This order is very interesting for both sides. In all cases, we will hit quickly in the center with ... c5 . }
3. c5
4. e3( 4.dxc5 { is not an issue since after }4...e6 { , }{ the pawn on  c5  will fall. } )( 4.c3 { is well met by }4...Nc6 { , and now }5.e3 { would transpose to   }4.e3 Nc6 5.c3 { , while after   }5.dxc5 e6 { , White cannot hang on to the pawn with }6.b4 { since }6...a5 7.b5 Ne7 { , }{ planning ... Ng6  next, punishes White's greedy play. Black will either collect the pawn on  c5  or start central expansion with ... e5 , taking advantage of White's lack of development and overextended queenside pawns. } )
4. Nc6( { The base position, when White must decide if }5.Nbd2 { or }5.c3 { is the way to go. } )
5. Nbd2( { The new main line. I think }5...Qb6 6.dxc5 { is a very interesting line for White. } )
5. Bg4{ Getting the bishop out of the pawn chain before playing ... e6  is very natural. }
6. h3{ This is the move that GM's Srinath Narayanan and Sahaj Grover recommend in their Chessable course. }
6. Bxf3
7. Nxf3
7. e6{ White can play now with  c3  or without  c3 . }
8. c3
8. Bd6
9. dxc5( 9.Bxd6 Qxd6 { is not dangerous for Black and the same applies to   }9.Qb3 Bxf4 10.Qxb7 Nxd4! { , or   }9.Ne5 cxd4 10.exd4 Qc7 11.Bb5 O-O { , when Black has no problems. } )
9. Bxc5{ There aren't any weaknesses for Black. }
10. Bd3
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. Bd6{ Forcing exchanges. }
12. Bxd6
12. Qxd6
13. Qe2
13. Ne5{ This is a totally equal position. ½-½ Petrosyan-Yu Yangyi, Sitges 2022. }
