[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. c5{ I like this move, hitting quickly in the center. }
3. e3{ The main line. }( 3.c3 Qb6 4.Qb3 Qxb3 5.axb3 cxd4 6.cxd4 Nc6 { is very pleasant for Black. } )( 3.dxc5 e6 { is not dangerous for Black. } )( 3.Bxb8 { is a very possible line, }3...Rxb8 4.dxc5 e6 5.Qd4 { (Not }5.b4 a5 6.a3 b6 { and White's structure collapses.)   }5...Ne7 { coming to  f5  or  c6 , and Black has a beautiful position. } )
3. cxd4{ This is the main idea for Black. }
4. exd4{ By transposition, we ended up in the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann. Not very worrying. }
4. Nc6( { At this moment, White must decide how to play, with }5.c3 { or }5.Nf3 { . } )
5. c3( { After }5.Bb5 { , I like }5...Qa5+ { , }{ forcing White to bring the knight to the  c3 -square, which is not ideal. Black can continue with ... Bf5  followed  by ... e6 , ... Rc8 , ... a6 , etc. } )
5. f6{ A very attractive idea that works tactically. }
6. Nf3{ The most natural move. }
6. Bf5( { There are some ideas with }6...g5?! { , but }7.Be3 { is good at this moment for White since now }7...Bf5 { is well met by }8.c4 { , }{ when Black cannot rely on the ... Nb4  resource due to  Qa4 +. } )
7. h3
7. g5{ With ... Qd7  coming, this seems OK for Black. }
8. Be3
8. Qd7( { As mentioned before, this is the difference: }9.c4 { can now be answered with }9...Nb4 { . } )
9. Nbd2( 9.Bd3 e6! { is strong, }{ aiming to recapture on  f5  with a pawn, creating a powerful pawn march on the kingside. } )
9. h5
10. Be2
10. e6{ With a very pleasant position for Black: ... Bd6 , ... Nge7 . }
