1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. c5{ I like this move, hitting quickly in the center. }
3. e3{ The main line. }( 3.c3 Qb6 4.Qb3 Qxb3 5.axb3 cxd4 6.cxd4 Nc6 { is very pleasant for Black. } )( 3.dxc5 e6 { is not dangerous for Black. } )( 3.Bxb8 { is a very possible line, }3...Rxb8 4.dxc5 e6 5.Qd4 { (Not }5.b4 a5 6.a3 b6 { and White's structure collapses.)   }5...Ne7 { coming to  f5  or  c6 , and Black has a beautiful position. } )
3. cxd4{ This is the main idea for Black. }
4. exd4{ By transposition, we ended up in the Exchange Variation of the Caro-Kann. Not very worrying. }
4. Nc6( { At this moment, White must decide how to play, with }5.c3 { or }5.Nf3 { . } )
5. c3( { After }5.Bb5 { , I like }5...Qa5+ { , }{ forcing White to bring the knight to the  c3 -square, which is not ideal. Black can continue with ... Bf5  followed  by ... e6 , ... Rc8 , ... a6 , etc. } )
5. f6{ A very attractive idea that works tactically. }
6. Bd3{ The critical line, with  Qh5 + ideas for White. }
6. e5{ Allowing  Qh5 + or  dxe5  and  Qh5 +. }
7. Qh5+{ The main line in this variation, but Black has enough resources! }
7. g6{ This is a very forced line for both sides. }
8. Bxg6+
8. hxg6
9. Qxh8
9. exf4
10. Qxg8{ An important moment for Black... }
10. Bf5{ The only move to fight for an advantage and initiative, defending  g6 , with ... Qe7 +, ... Qb6 , or ... Qd7  coming. }
11. Nf3
11. Qe7+{ White's king is in trouble. }
12. Kd1
12. O-O-O{ The only and very strong move! }
13. Nh4( 13.Re1 Qd7 14.Qh8 Bg7 15.Qh4 g5 { and Black is winning. } )
13. f3( { A very good move. Black's point is visible in the line }14.gxf3 Bd3 { and now White doesn't have the }15.Re1 { resource (which would have been the case had  13...Bd3  been played instead) due to }15...Bc2+ 16.Kd2 Bh6 { and Black is winning. } )
14. gxf3( 14.Nxf3 Bh6 { and the queen is trapped! } )( { Another possibility is }14.Re1 fxg2! 15.Nxg2 Qd7 { and Black is winning too. } )
14. Qd7
15. Nxf5
15. Qxf5
16. Nd2
