[White "21) Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. e4{ A dangerous gambit. White wants to develop quickly with  Nc3 ,  f3 ,  Nxf3 ,  Bd3 , or  Bc4  and castle, and attack quickly in the center. }( 2...e6 { for the French players, is a serious possibility, and the same with }2...c6 { for the Caro-Kann players. } )
2. dxe4{ Taking the pawn is the main move. }
3. Nc3( 3.f3? { is very bad because of }3...e5! { and after }4.dxe5 { , Black plays }4...Qxd1 { followed by ... exf3 , with a superior endgame. } )
3. Nf6
4. f3( { Finally sacrificing the pawn. }4.Bg5 { is not dangerous, as }4...Bf5 { is simply good, and }5.Qe2 { with the idea  Qb5 + }{ is well met by }5...Nbd7 { . Now }6.Bxf6 Nxf6 7.Qb5 Bd7 { is much better for Black. } )
4. exf3
5. Qxf3{ Taking with the queen is bad. Black can capture another pawn without problems. }
5. Qxd4
6. Be3
6. Qg4
7. Qf2
7. e5
8. Nb5
8. Bd6{ Black is two pawns up, and if necessary, Black can give a pawn back with a very good position. }
